tshades are the best Assassin<br><br>There’s nothing scientific about the poll, that kind of precision isn’t necessary. These opinions though could very well reflect that there are actual deficits with the Nightshade class that cause this “perception” that Nightshades are weaker.<br><br>It is also important to make the distinction that Nightshades are a unique class (and not a red-headed step child that keeps getting overlooked in each Assassin aspect). Assassins perform well in general, but when you break it down, the generality is weighted towards the perception of the other 2 Assassin classes. It’s not to say Nightshades are a bad class at all, but they get unfairly clustered with Assassin success that it is easy to look at their independent issues that still need to be addressed and think that all Assassins must be complete.<br> <br>========================================<br><br>NIGHTSHADE OFFENSE:<br><br>Aside from not being the best slash based Assassin or having the hardest critical attack of the Assassins, the deficit that is most striking and can be measured is the Nightshades shout versus the +453 bonus points that an Infiltrator can use to boost their damage output.<br><br>1) For example, the same template where a Nightshade has 40 weaponskill at level 50, can allow an Infiltrator to have 50 weaponskill at level 50. That adds 2 styles of utility and a 15% boost to casual melee damage. The utility of the shout is unmatched to that of a 9-second stun based off evade, and the damage output of the shout is embarrassing.<br><br>2) A template where a Nightshade that neglected dual wield for to focus on other skills, an Infiltrator can boost dual wield from level 1 to 30 with those bonus points. That is a 14.5% boost to casual melee damage (offhand swing percentage), and adds a plethora of styles for utility (despite that dual wield styles are generally useless, but that is a separate issue).<br><br>3) A template where a Nightshade has 20 Envenom can allow a similarly speced Infiltrator to have 35 Envenom. Those bonus points can increase poison tick damage by 35 points every 5 seconds, along with stronger debuff and snare utilities, or an additional +7 damage per second (+7dps).<br><br><br>The 15% average damage boost that the Infiltrator has in relation to the Nightshade’s melee damage is more difficult to calculate as a whole number than the bonus granted by Envenom where a definite dps number is obtained. The Envenom example actually obtains a whole number, such that a level 50 Infiltrator dishes out +7 more damage per second than a Nightshade. Over the course of 20 seconds, an Infiltrator dishes out +140 more points of damage than a Nightshade.<br><br>Some suggest that Nightshade melee damage get boosted through self buffs to match that of other Assassins. That really defeats the uniqueness of the Nightshade, and is a nuisance to have to constantly self buff just to keep up in terms of missing melee damage, there is a more appropriate Hibernian solution to the problem.<br><br>Nightshades can be said to have an offensive deficit of 140 damage every 20 seconds. A level 50 Nightshade shout that reliably deals an average of 140 damage on a 20 second timer could perfectly fill in the offensive deficit.<br><br>========================================<br><br>NIGHTSHADE DEFENSE:<br><br>By level 50, accounting for base stats, class bonuses, and not including any items:<br> <br>Saracens Infiltrators will have +35 hp more than Nightshades<br>British Infiltrators will have +70 hp more than Nightshades<br>Kobold Shadowblades will have +75 hp more than Nightshades<br>Norse Shadowblades will have +145 hp more than Nightshades<br><br>After Epic Armor with base CON:<br><br>Nightshades will have (+16) 56 CON<br>Saracen Infiltrators will have (+32) 82 CON<br>British Infiltrators will have (+32) 92 CON<br>Kobold Shadowblades will have (+42) 92 CON<br>Norse Shadowblades will have (+42) 112 CON (2x NS’s)<br><br>Total Hit Point comparison relative to Nightshades:<br><br>Saracens Infiltrators will have ~ +85 hp more than Nightshades<br>British Infiltrators will have ~ +120 hp more than Nightshades<br>Kobold Shadowblades will have ~ +155 hp more than Nightshades<br>Norse Shadowblades will have ~ +225 hp more than Nightshades<br><br>A recent Friday’s Grab Bag from the week before last revealed that CON has both an effect on Total Hit Points and Damage Reduction in combat. The twofold effect it has on the Nightshade validates the perception that Nightshades cannot withstand as much damage and are more easily damaged than the other Assassins.<br><br>The Epic Armor itself is not a core class issue because it is something that can be changed and is not built in to the class, so I will address that in a separate section. Fact remains aside from the Epic, that Nightshades will have 35-145 less hit points, along with less damage reduction. Elves and Lurikeen theoretically should be able to evade slightly better with a 5-10 stat point advantage in the chance to do so, but overall it doesn’t perform well enough to make up for lost hit points and damage reduction.<br><br>Again, an easy solution is to give the Nightshade a self buff spell to mimic having more hit points and damage absorbence. That wouldn’t make Nightshades any different in their defensive capabilities, but they now meet the minimum requirement of being magically enhanced for being from Hibernia.<br><br>Instead, a better solution might be to augment a different kind of defensive aspect. Allow for a scenario where Nightshades are slightly weaker face to face, but if they spot an enemy at range, they have a superior ranged attack than other Assassins have.<br><br>That can be achieved by upgrading their ranged attack damage near that of a baseline caster. A few major differences is that Casters will deal more damage through both stats, the specialization direct damage spells, criticals, realm abilities, and acuity buff they might have on.<br><br>========================================<br><br>REALM ABILITIES:<br><br>Reports show characters were previously able to train Augmented CON to get Mastery of Pain after the /respec got to keep it that way. In addition, the self heal from Ignore Pain still heals 100% if they didn’t /respec for the new version. I feel a complete realm ability wipe and /respec reset is due soon, and it should allow the chance for some realm abilities to get reanalyzed.<br><br>VIPER:<br><br>When realm abilities first came out and everyone speculated of the potential of each of the Assassin class specific abilities, community members thought:<br><br>1) Each were expensive for the ability they granted<br>2) (Shadow Run) &lt; (Vanish = Viper)<br>3) Shadow Run = Utility, Vanish = Utility / Damage, Viper = Damage<br>4) Shadow Run’s cost (10) relative to Vanish (14) and Viper (14) reflected that it was a weaker ability. (despite that they were all generally expensive)<br><br>After a Pendragon update that went live:<br><br>(10) Shadow Run = Utility<br>(10) Vanish = Utility / Damage<br>(14) Viper = Damage<br><br>It seemed like out of nowhere that Vanish got a reduction in its cost one patch without any explanation, such that it matches Shadow Run’s cost. Were Shadowblades and Nightshades simply forgotten?<br><br>Shadow Run is not an equal skill to Vanish. I personally believe Shadowrun should cost 8 points and last on a 1 minute timer, but that is a Shadowblade specific issue. Infiltrators have a damage/escape utility, depending on the situation, that now costs 10 points which is relatively fair for the ability versus the amount of points needed to purchase it, especially considering the loss of stealthed one-shotting.<br><br>Viper allows an assassin to double their poison damage. Between the level 40-50 range, the damage bonus of this ability is +384-480 damage over time.<br><br>Based on the 30 second timer, Viper can be applied to 2 targets for the full poison duration. However, every time I attempt this in RvR, I die. Nightshades are not meant to stick around long enough to attack a second target, stay long enough to overcome bladeturn and not miss on the target, while not getting instant mez/stunned (Nightshades are the only Assassin that has to face 2 realms that each have 2 classes that have instant forms of CC), and leaving enough endurance to try and make an sprinting escape. When doing so, I die before I can even rack up any points I might have made if the first target died. Trying to apply it to multiple targets is an unfruitful suicide mission.<br><br>Even when using it on an intended target, the ability is almost overkill, such that only 2 ticks go off before the target is dead from melee damage. In that case, it is worth only +128-160 to +384-480 points of bonus damage / 30 minutes for 14 points spent.<br><br>Compare that to the Sorceror ability that is an AE DoT. Level 50 Sorcerors with this ability where consistently hitting me for 109 damage per tick with this ability that stacks with other DoTs. It also costs 14 points and is on a 30 minute timer.<br><br>Nightshade Viper versus Sorceror Corporeal Disintegration<br><br>- Both cost 14 points, on a 30 minute timer<br><br>- Corporeal Disintegration is cast at range. Viper is applied in melee, and a hit must be scored in order to apply it.<br><br>- Corporeal Disintegration is an Area Effect. Viper is single target per melee hit per weapon swap / next successful melee hit.<br><br>- Corporeal Disintegration does a +109 damage tick that stacks with other dots. Viper will add +64-80 damage to a Nightshade’s existing DoT.<br><br>The purpose of this comparison is not to give Nightshade’s Corporeal Disintegration. It’s to compare the relative cost of the ability versus the rewards. Viper is not worth 14 points. It is more appropriately placed at 10 points, alongside the cost of Vanish where it was originally compared to as an equally viable ability if they had the same costs in the first place.<br><br>AUGMENT ACUITY:<br><br>At present, Augment Acuity does not raise any stat for the Nightshade. It is also the least useful of the stat buffs, even if it did buff a stat, because spell damage is almost never a factor in Nightshade encounters. This bug needs to be fixed, as well as some kind of official statement as to what stat affects Nightshade magic (if any).<br><br>Unlike Augment Dexterity, Constitution, and Quickness, Augment Acuity only leads to one other skill, Wild Arcana. Each other augmentation leads to at least 2 other skills to choose from, that stretch out the benefit of being able to spend less points for other abilities by sharing the same prerequisite augmentation.<br><br>It got me thinking about how Rangers face the same dilemma, so I started looking for another ability with Augment Acuity that could be added that would benefit Rangers and Nightshades. There weren’t any perfect fits. After some thinking and being reminded that Hibernia is the magic realm, I thought what if there was a realm ability that increased the chances of procing a magical weapon effect? It would fit perfectly as a second ability that requires Augment Acuity as a prerequisite and would apply to both Rangers and Nightshades. Thus, after meeting the Augment Acuity prerequisite, it now opens up 2 skills instead of one:<br><br>Wild Arcana<br>Passive / Acuity 2 / +5% chance to critical on DOTs per level<br><br>Unleashed Arcana<br>Passive / Acuity 2 / +5% chance to proc weapon per level<br><br>If Unleashed Arcana is not implemented, it is still a good point to address that Augment Acuity still leads to only one other skill. It happens to fit both the role of the stat and the realm very well that it should be given considerable thought.<br><br>========================================<br><br>EPIC ARMOR DEFICIT:<br><br>The Nightshade Epic grants the least amount of hit points of all the Assassin classes, further stretching their gap between them and Infiltrators and Shadowblades. I recommend upping the +CON bonus to +32 instead of +16 so the deficit isn’t so extreme and will give Nightshades around +55 more hit points to work with.<br><br>One of the unknowns is which stat really affects Nightshade magic. IF it is one of the main stats like STR, DEX, or QUI, then Nightshades benefit equally in buffing their ranged attack in the same way Infiltrators and Shadowblades can use those Epic Armor bonuses to increase their ranged attacks. IF it is determined that INT is the casting stat for Nightshades, their Epic should reflect an equivalent stat bonus to INT to compensate for that ~ +50 INT.<br><br>========================================<br><br>PROPOSED SOLUTIONS:<br><br>To sum up all the Nightshade fixes in relation to the areas that need to be addressed:<br><br>Nightshade Offensive Deficit:<br><br>- Spell Variance that of a 2/3 specialized caster<br>- Base Shout of 140 base damage by level 48<br><br><br>Nightshade Defensive Deficit:<br><br>- Direct Damage spell of 175 base damage by level 50<br><br><br>Realm Ability Deficit:<br><br>- Viper cost of 10 points<br>- Fix Augment Acuity raise a stat<br>- Add Unleashed Arcana as a 2nd ability to choose from Augment Acuity<br><br><br>Epic Armor Deficit:<br><br>- Change +16 CON to +32 CON bonus from Epic Armor<br>- If INT affects Nightshade magic, appropriately include ~ +50 INT into the armor.<br><br>========================================<br><br>I won’t settle for anything less for Nightshades anymore. It’s been too long, and I think I am trying too hard that it’s not worth the effort I put into it. These solutions are here to find creative ways of addressing deficits that fit the Nightshade class and not to overpower them, and are not the kind of things that are “cool” or that I would like to see Nightshades have, they are needed.<br><br>I end the Nightshade Report with this question...<br><br><br><br>Should I keep trying?<br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uolmoss.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Olmoss</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_bluespot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(5/19/02 8:31:24 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3300.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Elaa?s Unofficial Nightshade Report 5/19/02</span><hr size=1>  Elaa, meet Katt, <br> Katt, meet Elaa<br><br>    Katt is prolly the closest folks with mains as Bards have to an &quot;Elaa&quot; and you really aught to get togeather and compare notes, especially after Katt posted a very simular thread here:<br><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://vnboards.ign.com/message.asp?topic=29837077&start=29871449">vnboards.ign.com/message....t=29871449</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>on the usefulness of the efforts and &quot;How things Work&quot; at Mythic.<br>and for more discussion of the same issue<br><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://vnboards.ign.com/message.asp?topic=29830779&start=29837696">vnboards.ign.com/message....t=29837696</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br><br><br> My own conculsion from reading that and simular threads is that the decision making folks are somewhat divorced from the main game ..and tend to only hear the &quot;roars&quot; of the crowd. As Hibernians shrink in population it becomes increasingly difficult to have a &quot;voice&quot;. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uolmoss.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Olmoss</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_bluespot.gif" BORDER=0> at: 5/19/02 8:42:4