se those are class core issues. The rest are appendages to the Nightshade class by means of stats and realm ability adjustments.<br><br>- Spell Variance that of a 2/3 specialized caster<br>- Base Shout of 140 base damage by level 48<br>- Direct Damage spell of 175 base damage by level 50<br><br>- Viper cost of 10 points<br>- Fix Augment Acuity raise a stat<br>- Add Unleashed Arcana as a 2nd ability to choose from Augment Acuity<br>- Change +16 CON to +32 CON bonus from Epic Armor<br>- If INT affects Nightshade magic, appropriately include ~ +50 INT into the armor.<br><br>Here are some responses to some posts made so far. I also ask that everyone making comparisons to read the actual list of fixes, and not to compare only Assassin versus Assassin combat situations when looking at what is addressed and analyzing the proposed fixes:<br><br><br>Conjoy –<br><br>&gt;&gt; “I think that buffs are a much more *Hibernian* way of implementing the fixes. Furthermore if they could be added so as to be friendly castable, and thus improve NS viability in PvE groups this would be good too.”<br><br>One of the downsides to buffs is that they can be overridden. For example, an equally buffed Nightshade that encounters an equally buffed Shadowblade will not stand toe to toe because of the core class differences. Buffs are an artificiality that is added to the class. Compare a Druid buffed Nightshade to a Shaman buffed Shadowblade, or a Cleric buffed Infiltrator, the Nightshade that can self buff is likely to have overridden defensive buffs. A Nightshade that has to use defensive buffs to fight like an Infiltrator or Shadowblade will find themselves at a disadvantage in these situations.<br><br>Another complexity is what happens when the self buff wears off when the Nightshade is stealthing. The Nightshade then has to find a spot to safely unstealth, just to rebuff just so they can stand toe to toe with another Assassin. An Assassin playing cat and mouse against a Nightshade can wait in the area for the Nightshade to have to rebuff, then strike.<br><br>As far as improving Nightshade viability in PvE groups, I see the PvE grouping issue as an Assassin wide issue, and not something specific to Nightshades, that can be addressed in Assassin-wide fixes.<br> <br><br>Woopya –<br><br>&gt;&gt; “However, I would like to see a different approach to solving our defensive woes. Id like to see us either have much higher natural resistance rates compared to sbs and inf, or id like to see us get a self buff to that effect. In particular, i want our reistance to poison much higher than other assassins. If we resist poisons much more often than they do, the fight becomes a little bit more even. Most of the time shades lose pure mellee fights to either SB or INF(equal lvl) as it stands now. But what if that sbs or inf's poison was resisted half of the time?”<br><br>The defensive proposal of self buff to resist poisons you suggest instead of the Nightshade nuke fix only addresses Assassin versus Assassin combat. The hit points that the other Assassins have apply to ALL encounters, not just Assassin vs Assassin combat. Your proposal narrows it to a specific type of encounter, and does not help the Nightshade in encounters against other classes so the defensive deficit still remains.<br><br>It is not a bad idea, but does not completely address that type of deficit that can be used in all encounters. It is something that makes the “cool” list of things to have.<br><br><br>The Stranger –<br><br>&gt;&gt; “I don't see 50th assassins from far away enough to care, and I wouldn't spoil my potential for a critical strike and stun on anyone else in order to shoot at them.”<br><br>Just as I responded to Woopya, a Nightshade’s defensive deficit is not limited to Assassin vs Assassin combat. It is a utility meant for a different kind of encounter, and again is not fair to narrow a Nightshade fix to their defensive deficit solely in terms of performing only against other Assassins.<br><br><br>Old Mill –<br><br>&gt;&gt; “so your solutions are to give nightshades more hps, to get them equal with shadowblades(our whopping realm unique ability)”<br><br>I conveniently listed every single fix, please go through the list and show me where I come up with a solution to give more hit points to Nightshades to equal them with Shadowblades? Nightshades only get a +16 CON bonus through their Epic Armor and Shadowblades get a +42 CON bonus? That has nothing to do with the Shadowblade realm unique ability. After all hit points are tallied as was in the original post:<br><br>Total Hit Point comparison relative to Nightshades with Epic Armor:<br><br>Kobold Shadowblades will have ~ +155 hp more than Nightshades<br>Norse Shadowblades will have ~ +225 hp more than Nightshades<br><br>All that I proposed is a boost to the CON bonus in the Nightshade Epic Armor from +16 to +32 CON, and has nothing to do with bringing Nightshades to have an equal number of hit points as a Shadowblade. Take note this is not a fix to a Nightshade inherent ability, this is a fix to a deficiency in the Nightshade Epic that causes an even steeper divide in hit points and damage absorbance between Nightshades and the other Assassins.<br> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uelaa.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Elaa</A> at: 5/20/02 2:28:22 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uwoopya.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Woopya</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(5/20/02 11:49:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3300.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> /reply2</span><hr size=1> I have to disagree(respectfully) with you again on some minor points about